issue.title: use of `$FUNCNAME` when `set -u` is in place and `FUNCNAME` was unset
issue.body:
## Describe the bug Throughout the code `$FUNCNAME` is used, which causes an unbound error, if `set -u` is in place and `FUNCNAME` was unset. Interestingly, which I don't quite understand why, one can `unset FUNCNAME` even outside a function (where I thought it wasn't supposed to exist) and it will have the effect of it being no longer special. ## Expected behavior I guess `${FUNCNAME-}` or so should be used. ## Additional context If it helps, I could provide a PR, but I have no idea which value we should use (especially also in the `FUNCNAME[i]` cases)... simply `unknown`?
The empty string? Though that would look ugly in many error messages (because of the `"bash_completion: : message`)... so maybe use something `${FUNCNAME:+"$FUNCNAME": }` and print the `: ` via that (and only if there is a funcname? Thanks, Chris.

commits.message: feat(_comp_get_fist_arg): support "-o GLOB" to skip optargs

fix(_comp_count_args): exclude <>& from wordbreaks as _comp_initialize

In the current implementation, to count the number of arguments, we
reassemble `cword` and `words` by specified exclude chars (i.e.,
characters that should not be considered word breaks even though they
are in COMP_WORDBREAKS).  The reassembly by the top-level
`_comp_initialize` always specify `<>&` as exclude chars, but the
current implementaion of `_comp_count_args` do not specify them.  This
patch specifies `<>&` for `_comp_count_args` in accordance with
`_comp_initialize`.

perf(_comp_count_args): skip reinitializing cword and words

In most of the contexts calling `_comp_count_args` in the current
codebase, `cword` and `words` are already initialized with the same
set of exclude chars (-n chars) by _comp_initialize, so there seems to
be no need to again reassemble `cword` and `words`.  This patch
removes the redundant initialization of `cword` and `words`.

* When `_comp_initialize` is called without `-s` or `-n chars` and
  `_comp_count_args` is called with an empty $1, they are compatible
  so `cword` and `words` outside can be directly used.

* `7z` and `nslookup` specify the same set of exclude chars as
  `_comp_initialize`, so existing `cword` and `words` are compatible.

Nevertheless, we need to reinitialize `cword` and `words` when the
specified exclude chars are different from those specified to
_comp_initialize.

* The `ssh` completion calls `_comp_count_args` with excluding `=`
  while it calls `_comp_initialize` with `-n :`.

* The `chown` completion calls `_comp_count_args` with excluding `:`
  while it calls `_comp_initialize` with `-sn :`.

* The `nc` completions calls `_comp_count_args` without exclude chars
  while it calls `_comp_initialize` with `-n :`.

* The completions for `chmod`, `cryptsetup`, `hcitool`, `mkinitrd`,
  `patch`, `quota`, and `zopflipng` does not specify exclude chars to
  `_comp_count_args` while they specify `-s` to `_comp_initialize`.

It is not clear whether these discrepancies are intended ones are not,
but this patch tries to keep the current behavior by explicitly
specifying the original exclude chars.

fix(_comp_count_args): skip reassembling cword and words

These completions induce reassembling `cword` and `words` inside
`_comp_count_args`, but they are likely to be intended to be the same
as outside `cword` and `words`.  We just skip the reassembling by
dropping `-n ""` or `-n :`.

issue.title: use of `$FUNCNAME` when `set -u` is in place and `FUNCNAME` was unset
issue.body:
## Describe the bug Throughout the code `$FUNCNAME` is used, which causes an unbound error, if `set -u` is in place and `FUNCNAME` was unset. Interestingly, which I don't quite understand why, one can `unset FUNCNAME` even outside a function (where I thought it wasn't supposed to exist) and it will have the effect of it being no longer special. ## Expected behavior I guess `${FUNCNAME-}` or so should be used. ## Additional context If it helps, I could provide a PR, but I have no idea which value we should use (especially also in the `FUNCNAME[i]` cases)... simply `unknown`?
The empty string? Though that would look ugly in many error messages (because of the `"bash_completion: : message`)... so maybe use something `${FUNCNAME:+"$FUNCNAME": }` and print the `: ` via that (and only if there is a funcname? Thanks, Chris.

comment.body:
You shouldn't unset the Bash special variables in an interactive *Bash* session even though it is possible. At least, bash-completion cannot be responsible for every kind of broken environment. There are many different ways to break the environment by removing or disabling the Bash built-in features.
- For example, one can overwrite builtin commands by functions, aliases, etc. To protect ourselves, one might use the `builtin` builtin, but a function or an alias can also overwrite the `builtin` builtin. One might then think about using the POSIX mode to access the builtins directly, but it again fails when the builtins are disabled by `enable -n`. If the `enable` builtin itself is disabled, then there is no way to recover the builtins.
- For another example, one can mark random variables `readonly` at the top level of the shell context (e.g. `readonly i`), and then any local variables of the same name cannot be defined.
- Unsetting `FUNCNAME` is a breakage of the fundamental environment at the same level. There are many similar variables including `BASH`, `COMP_WORDBREAKS`, `LINENO`, `OSTYPE`, `PATH`, `PWD`, etc. It might be worked around by checking the existence of all the variables, but it complicates the codebase unnecessarily.

I have a doubt about complicating the codebase just to protect us from such unrealistic cases.

A part of the reason that Bash allows unsetting these variables is for compatibility with the POSIX standard. For example, the standard does not define the variable `FUNCNAME`, so the variable should be able to be used by an application program written in a portable shell script. However, it is practically impossible to mix up the POSIX scripts (that use the variable names conflicting with the Bash special variables) and the Bash scripts. If you would like to unset `FUNCNAME`, you should do it in a standalone portable POSIX script. On the other hand, `bash-completion` is written in a Bash script (but not in a POSIX script), and it doesn't assume the POSIX environment where Bash features (including `FUNCNAME`) are not available or turned off.

fix: add misc fixes (misc-1)

fix(compat): find compat dir for prefix-install

With the current implementation, if the main file of `bash_completion`
is the one installed with a prefix, bash-completion fails to find the
compat dir `bash_completion.d`.  As a consequence, the 2.11 compat
functions are not loaded by default.  This causes issues with external
completions using the old interface.

issue.body:
## Describe the bug Throughout the code `$FUNCNAME` is used, which causes an unbound error, if `set -u` is in place and `FUNCNAME` was unset. Interestingly, which I don't quite understand why, one can `unset FUNCNAME` even outside a function (where I thought it wasn't supposed to exist) and it will have the effect of it being no longer special. ## Expected behavior I guess `${FUNCNAME-}` or so should be used. ## Additional context If it helps, I could provide a PR, but I have no idea which value we should use (especially also in the `FUNCNAME[i]` cases)... simply `unknown`?
The empty string? Though that would look ugly in many error messages (because of the `"bash_completion: : message`)... so maybe use something `${FUNCNAME:+"$FUNCNAME": }` and print the `: ` via that (and only if there is a funcname? Thanks, Chris.

comment.body:
Oh, I haven't really checked whether any of `bash`’s other "special" variables that can be unset are used in a fashion that would cause errors when `set -u` is in use.

Maybe that should be done.
